  "articleSummary": "The article critiques the dogmatic application of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), arguing that equating \"small\" with \"cohesive\" leads to over-fragmentation, not clarity. It warns against \"Single-Purpose People\" who create codebases with excessive files, tangled dependencies, brittle tests, and lost velocity—citing React/Redux as a common example. The tone is analytical with a frustrated edge, using metaphors like \"file system shrapnel\" and \"Rube Goldberg architecture\" to frame the chaos. The intended audience is software developers and architects, with the core thesis that SRP should be applied at a meaningful level of cohesion, not as a mandate for atomic units.",
